Best wings in the bay area. the wings are so candy and their chinese food is pretty smack too. if you need more food other than just the wings, get the fried potstickers, black bean noodles, dry and fried calamari and any of the fried rice options. *DRY-FRIED CHICKEN WING GOODNESS* San Tung is a must for me whenever I visit SF. I dream about San Tung's chicken wings and I eat a lot of fried chicken (Southern and Korean-style). I've been impressed by the food and have been lucky enough to forgo lines because of frequent take-out orders. I think I've probably eaten at the actual restaurant one time, but have ordered take-out dozens. If you're coming with a large party, expect long wait times (unless you go late at night) and decent/not-amazing service. If you order to-go, be prepared for food to take anywhere from 15-30 minutes. PARKING: Street parking only with metered parking right in front of the restaurant. It's in the Inner Sunset District, so you can find residential parking and walk on over. Also within walking distance from the N-line. INTERIOR: They have large group tables (think lazy Susans) and tables for four inside the restaurant. Not much of a waiting area inside the building so will have to wait outside to be seated. Not as cramped inside as say Burma Superstar. I don't think much of the interior and decor have changed since San Tung has opened. It's your typical old-school Chinese restaurant. FOOD: Besides the crispy, juicy, sweet, and spicy dry-fried CHICKEN WINGS (12 wings with every order), I really enjoy their FLOUNDER. I've had the black bean version and the dry-fried version. Both are incredible. The dry-fried will be like the fish version of the fried chicken. The flounder is crispy on the outside and so soft and flaky on the inside. Their BLACK BEAN NOODLES are Chinese-style, so expect a lot of grease, seafood, and a lot more salty flavor compared to the Korean-style jajangmyun. An order of black bean noodle is decent enough for 2-3 people to share. Huge for one person. PORK DUMPLINGS are soft, juicy, and meaty more than dough-y. If you need a veggie, STRING BEANS are the way to go. Not going to be steamed, but very flavorful and dry-sauteed = no limp string beans, on the sweet side. PRICE: Not going to lie, it can get pricey. I've spent anywhere from $15 to $25 per person here before. If you take to-go and eat it with rice at home, maybe you can bring down the cost. Overall: GET YOURSELF SOME DAMN CHICKEN WINGS.

After 23 years of living in the Bay Area, I finally tried San tung, and boy, am I kicking myself for not trying it sooner!! We went on a Sunday around 11am, and there wasn't much of a wait! My group is pretty basic and ordered the original dry chicken wings, black bean noodles, and sautéed string beans. I truly understand why their chicken is named one of the best in the bay - the sauce coats the skin perfectly, but the batter is still so light and crispy. The chicken is juicy, and regardless of whether or not you like fried chicken, you will love this! The black bean noodles were a little on the saltier side imo but still tasty, and I enjoyed the chewiness of the noodles. The string beans were a solid dish as well. This ended up being plenty of food for the 4 of us, and I will definitely be back :)

One of my favorite places in SF, I always have to make a stop if I'm in the city because of these wings! There's no where else that makes wings comparable to San Tung. The dry wet wings are crispy on the outside, tender and flavorful on the inside and the sauce is just the perfect garlicky, sweet, and salty addition. Even though there's 12 pieces, it is just enough for two people to share. I usually get a side of string beans and rice to go with the meal. And I always get a togo order with the sauce on the side to bring back home. That way the wings don't get soggy!

Came here with friends for lunch, and I was the only one here for the first time. Came about 1pm, and waited a bit for a table for four, as this place is VERY popular! The food is the reason to come here, as the ambience is actually very typical of a restaurant in Chinatown rather than an upscale suburban fine dining restaurant - but that's the best reason to come, for good food! The place itself is clean, busy (read "crowded") and well lit, and a bustling experience to be sure. We were seated and promptly given menus and waters, and a server arrived within a couple of minutes for our order, but the menu is several pages so we needed a bit more time. The draw for us were the wings and the fish, so those were for sure items to order, but we also added a few more items. Ultimately we settled on egg rolls and kimchi for appetizers, original dry fried chicken wings, dried sautéed string beans, dry fried flounder fillet, black mushroom and tofu (bean curd), vegetable chow mein and vegetable fried rice. Considering the volume of people eating, the food came rather quickly, albeit in batches of one or two plates at a time. The kitchen itself extends all the way to the back, and we could see into it - it was big and well lit, with a lot of help! We soon ran out of room on the table, and I initially wondered why we were given small plates, the kind you usually find for bread use, rather than regular dinner service size plates; but they would definitely not fit with all the food plates people ordered. The kimchi was very good, tasty and spicy with red peppers. Not everyone liked it, but I devoured it almost by myself. The egg rolls were good, crispy and not greasy with that delicious red sweet sauce - yummy. The vegetable chow mein was rather tasteless, very bland. The vegetable fried rice was almost as bland, and rather mushy as well. These two items had us worried about the rest of the food. However, the stars of the meal were the chicken wings and the fish fillets. They were the two go-to items even before we got here, and they did not fail us. The wings were cooked well and slathered in tasty (and sticky!) sauce. The fish, battered and cooked nicely, were just as tasty in their own sauce. And the pieces were just the right size for a bite or two for each piece. The other dishes were good - the black mushrooms and tofu were plentiful and in a brown sauce. I used the fried rice for the base, rather than ordering a side of brown rice. The rice was mushy, but with the mushrooms and tofu it was fine for the use. The beans were good as well, tasty and firm. There were a lot of them on the plate, almost too much for even the four of us, so some went home in a take-home box. The service was good, with water and tea refills when needed, and our server Weina Shi was very efficient and professional. Overall, a nice experience and good food. The chow mein and rice were disappointing, but the chicken wings and fish were the saviors of the day; I feel other specialty dishes may be as outstanding, and I hope to test my theory in a future visit!

You need to stop by San Tung. 10/10 recommend. I'm still thinking about them 2 days later.

San Tungs is exactly what you expect. An ICONIC hole in the wall Chinese place in San Francisco. If you go during peak lunch or dinner hours, expect to wait at least a hour. San Tungs has a more communal vibe, so expect to possibly sit next to strangers (there's still plenty of room for both parties don't worry). I also highly recommend ordering family style (sharing multiple entrees among your group). I love going here, and here is what I usually order (some are must orders!!) San Tung's Famous Chicken Wings (Rating 5/5, MUST ORDER) -This mix of sweet and spicy sauce is INCREDIBLE, not only on the chicken, but if you get white rice, mix it with it! -The chicken wings are always made to order and are always fresh, and I've been here 10+ times and have ordered upwards to 5 orders for catering for parties Peanut Sauce Noodles (Rating 5/5, MUST ORDER) -Allergy warning: contains pieces of Scallop, Shrimp and peanut (obviously). -The sauce is just amazing, and the noodles are cooked perfectly (not too firm, not too soft) -Messy to serve Stir Fried String Beans (Rating 4/5 - Great vegetable dish) -The string beans here are made pretty standard, but the sauce is a bit sweet with a very minor kick. This is always my groups go to "healthy vegetable" option. Fried Sweet and Sour Pork (Rating 4/5 - Great meat dish) -My most recent visit was the first time I got this, and I have to say I was not disappointed. If you are looking for another meat this, I would recommend grabbing this item. -Fried perfectly well, and was boneless, additionally the sweet and sour sauce is not like your Panda Express, and tastes really good. Pork and Chive Dumplings (Rating 3/5 - Really average/standard) -To be honest the dumplings are really average - I would get it as a nice appetizer/filler, but you could definitely skip it and just order another order of the wings. The only reason why I give this place 4/5 stars overall is because of the service, and cleanliness. However, it's kind of expected for a Chinese place with this kind of popularity. The waiters are constantly busy, and probably won't refill your glass or tea unless you ask directly. Additionally, I've come in and had to ask for new dishware/utensils because sometimes there is still minor left over grime. tl;dr Expect high wait times, and mediocre service, but leave happy and full because the food is amazing!

    *DRY-FRIED CHICKEN WING GOODNESS*

    San Tung is a must for me whenever I visit SF. I dream about San Tung's chicken wings and I eat a lot of fried chicken (Southern and Korean-style). I've been impressed by the food and have been lucky enough to forgo lines because of frequent take-out orders. I think I've probably eaten at the actual restaurant one time, but have ordered take-out dozens. If you're coming with a large party, expect long wait times (unless you go late at night) and decent/not-amazing service. If you order to-go, be prepared for food to take anywhere from 15-30 minutes.

    PARKING: Street parking only with metered parking right in front of the restaurant. It's in the Inner Sunset District, so you can find residential parking and walk on over. Also within walking distance from the N-line.

    INTERIOR: They have large group tables (think lazy Susans) and tables for four inside the restaurant. Not much of a waiting area inside the building so will have to wait outside to be seated. Not as cramped inside as say Burma Superstar. I don't think much of the interior and decor have changed since San Tung has opened. It's your typical old-school Chinese restaurant.

    FOOD: Besides the crispy, juicy, sweet, and spicy dry-fried CHICKEN WINGS (12 wings with every order), I really enjoy their FLOUNDER. I've had the black bean version and the dry-fried version. Both are incredible. The dry-fried will be like the fish version of the fried chicken. The flounder is crispy on the outside and so soft and flaky on the inside. Their BLACK BEAN NOODLES are Chinese-style, so expect a lot of grease, seafood, and a lot more salty flavor compared to the Korean-style jajangmyun. An order of black bean noodle is decent enough for 2-3 people to share. Huge for one person. PORK DUMPLINGS are soft, juicy, and meaty more than dough-y. If you need a veggie,  STRING BEANS are the way to go. Not going to be steamed, but very flavorful and dry-sauteed = no limp string beans, on the sweet side.

    PRICE: Not going to lie, it can get pricey. I've spent anywhere from $15 to $25 per person here before. If you take to-go and eat it with rice at home, maybe you can bring down the cost.

    Overall: GET YOURSELF SOME DAMN CHICKEN WINGS.

    Came here with friends for lunch, and I was the only one here for the first time. Came about 1pm, and waited a bit for a table for four, as this place is VERY popular! The food is the reason to come here, as the ambience is actually very typical of a restaurant in Chinatown rather than an upscale suburban fine dining restaurant - but that's the best reason to come, for good food! The place itself is clean, busy (read "crowded") and well lit, and a bustling experience to be sure.

    We were seated and promptly given menus and waters, and a server arrived within a couple of minutes for our order, but the menu is several pages so we needed a bit more time. The draw for us were the wings and the fish, so those were for sure items to order, but we also added a few more items.

    Ultimately we settled on egg rolls and kimchi for appetizers, original dry fried chicken wings, dried sautéed string beans, dry fried flounder fillet, black mushroom and tofu (bean curd), vegetable chow mein and vegetable fried rice.

    Considering the volume of people eating, the food came rather quickly, albeit in batches of one or two plates at a time. The kitchen itself extends all the way to the back, and we could see into it - it was big and well lit, with a lot of help! We soon ran out of room on the table, and I initially wondered why we were given small plates, the kind you usually find for bread use, rather than regular dinner service size plates; but they would definitely not fit with all the food plates people ordered.

    The kimchi was very good, tasty and spicy with red peppers. Not everyone liked it, but I devoured it almost by myself. The egg rolls were good, crispy and not greasy with that delicious red sweet sauce - yummy.

    The vegetable chow mein was rather tasteless, very bland. The vegetable fried rice was almost as bland, and rather mushy as well. These two items had us worried about the rest of the food.

    However, the stars of the meal were the chicken wings and the fish fillets. They were the two go-to items even before we got here, and they did not fail us. The wings were cooked well and slathered in tasty (and sticky!) sauce. The fish, battered and cooked nicely, were just as tasty in their own sauce. And the pieces were just the right size for a bite or two for each piece.

    The other dishes were good - the black mushrooms and tofu were plentiful and in a brown sauce. I used the fried rice for the base, rather than ordering a side of brown rice. The rice was mushy, but with the mushrooms and tofu it was fine for the use. The beans were good as well, tasty and firm. There were a lot of them on the plate, almost too much for even the four of us, so some went home in a take-home box.

    The service was good, with water and tea refills when needed, and our server Weina Shi was very efficient and professional.
    Overall, a nice experience and good food. The chow mein and rice were disappointing, but the chicken wings and fish were the saviors of the day; I feel other specialty dishes may be as outstanding, and I hope to test my theory in a future visit!

    This restaurant has sat in my collections for a LONG TIME. And this past weekend, I had the opportunity to try it. Oh boy is it good. It's really good.

    The wait wasn't bad on a Sunday night at 6 PM. We waited about 30 mins before being seated at the window seat. That didn't matter much to me because when the food arrived (rather quickly), I didn't pay attention to the many heads staring in.

    The food is amazing. We got the Mongolian beef, the wings, and the black bean noodles. All of it was amazing. The black bean noodles were well done, with a good amount of meat variety and enough sauce to coat the noodles in the savory sauce. No weird half sauce covered noodles here.

    The Mongolian beef was awesome! The meat was so tender and the dish is very savory. The crunchy noodles at the bottom of the dish worked very well with the tender beef.

    The star of the show were the wings. It's double fried and completely drowned in a sweet and tangy sauce. I'm sure it's made with honey. Anyways, the wings itself were the right amount of crunch and the copious amount of sauce really made the dish shine. All in all, I can see why people come to San Tung for the wings!

    You need to stop by San Tung. 10/10 recommend. I'm still thinking about them 2 days later.

    Oh god, I can't even express how much I love San Tung.

    Whenever friends come from out of town, I always take them here. Parking isn't tooooo bad, if you get lucky, you'll be able to find parking in front of the store, but if not, there's plenty of street parking in the surrounding neighborhoods.

    There's no online waitlist- you have to physically come inside the store and write your name on a whiteboard. It's always packed in there, but they have an amazing front of house staff who clean up & seat customers super quickly. Even with a waitlist of 30+ groups, I've still been seated in under an hour.

    My go to is always the chicken wings & stir fried green beans. Seaweed soup & black bean noodles are also good, but I find that an order of chicken wings & green beans is perfect to feed 2-3 people. A lot of times, I'll order an extra order of chicken wings to take with me to go.

    San Tungs is exactly what you expect. An ICONIC hole in the wall Chinese place in San Francisco. If you go during peak lunch or dinner hours, expect to wait at least a hour. San Tungs has a more communal vibe, so expect to possibly sit next to strangers (there's still plenty of room for both parties don't worry). I also highly recommend ordering family style (sharing multiple entrees among your group).

    I love going here, and here is what I usually order (some are must orders!!)

    San Tung's Famous Chicken Wings (Rating 5/5, MUST ORDER)
    -This mix of sweet and spicy sauce is INCREDIBLE, not only on the chicken, but if you get white rice, mix it with it!
    -The chicken wings are always made to order and are always fresh, and I've been here 10+ times and have ordered upwards to 5 orders for catering for parties

    Peanut Sauce Noodles (Rating 5/5, MUST ORDER)
    -Allergy warning: contains pieces of Scallop, Shrimp and peanut (obviously).
    -The sauce is just amazing, and the noodles are cooked perfectly (not too firm, not too soft)
    -Messy to serve

    Stir Fried String Beans (Rating 4/5 - Great vegetable dish)
    -The string beans here are made pretty standard, but the sauce is a bit sweet with a very minor kick. This is always my groups go to "healthy vegetable" option.

    Fried Sweet and Sour Pork (Rating 4/5 - Great meat dish)
    -My most recent visit was the first time I got this, and I have to say I was not disappointed. If you are looking for another meat this, I would recommend grabbing this item.
    -Fried perfectly well, and was boneless, additionally the sweet and sour sauce is not like your Panda Express, and tastes really good.

    Pork and Chive Dumplings (Rating 3/5 - Really average/standard)
    -To be honest the dumplings are really average - I would get it as a nice appetizer/filler, but you could definitely skip it and just order another order of the wings.

    The only reason why I give this place 4/5 stars overall is because of the service, and cleanliness. However, it's kind of expected for a Chinese place with this kind of popularity. The waiters are constantly busy, and probably won't refill your glass or tea unless you ask directly. Additionally, I've come in and had to ask for new dishware/utensils because sometimes there is still minor left over grime.

    tl;dr Expect high wait times, and mediocre service, but leave happy and full because the food is amazing!

    my experience -
    san tung is a classic spot for family gatherings and people to grab lunch/dinner. i have been here since i was a little girl and the hype still lives on. there used to be a san tung 2 but it has recently closed down. i came on a saturday night with a group of 6 and we waited 1.5 hours. for those who know the restaurant well, this is a typical wait time as it is not too big but a very popular spot for locals and tourists. they have a large selection on their menu but people come for the classic dishes which is what we got as well.

    food - the food took a really long time for our table. others who sat down after us got food before us and the waiter was nice enough to check and right after it came out.

    dry sauteed chicken wings (3 orders x $14.50) -
    you cannot say that you've eaten or been to san tung until you've had their chicken wings. one order is perfect for two people if they are both super hunger.

    combination fried rice -
    the fried rice was way better than the black bean noodles. this was a perfect match with the dry sauteed chicken wings made with veggies, shrimp, beef, and calamari.

    string beans ($12.50) -
    another delicious classic dish! this is a great dish to pair with the chicken. we all enjoyed the flavors in the dish.

    black bean noodles ($12) -
    this dish was just okay, not the greatest and you can definitely find better black bean noodles elsewhere. you can skip out on this dish and save your stomach for more chicken or dumplings. it is very slimy and the flavor is not fully there.

    price -
    this meal was super filling and we were able to finish every dish (and we were super full)

    payment -
    if you are with a large group and want to split the check, you can only put it on two cards.

    service -
    the service is exactly what you would expect at a crowded chinese restaurant, super fast-paced.

    overall -
    if you come here with a big group, i recommend the fried rice, chicken and green beans. i do want to try their dumplings because it is what they're most known for but we were too full. i would definitely come back for them!
